review_blob: The beer pours a dark orange color with an off-white head. The aroma blends buttery sweet malts, pine, grapefruit, spruce tips, and orange peel. The beers flavor is mildly sweet, but theres a bit more bitterness. The pine, grapefruit, and citrus rind also appear in flavor. The beer has a slick texture, but the mile carbonation keeps the beer from being too heavy on the palate.
beer_name: Cigar City Jai Alai India Pale Ale

review_blob: The beer isnt as dark or as thick as I would like when tackling these intense of flavors. Also, the aroma is nice, but the flavor is more roasted peanuts than peanut butter. Great idea, but less than ideal execution.

The beer pours a clear copper color with a medium-sized cream-colored head. The aroma blends cereal malt,, toasted malt, hay, caramel, and a subtle cocoa note, and the taste is slightly bitter and slightly sweet with the dominant flavors being earthy and caramel. The aftertaste is quite malty with some hop flavor lingering. The mouthfeel combines a medium-light body, light carbonation, and a slick texture.

The beer pours a cloudy dark straw color with a medium white head. The aroma is packed full of hops (citrus and grassy) with underlying pils malts. The taste is slightly sweet with a lot of citrus hop flavor. The malt bill drinks lightly. The palate fuses a slick texture, light carbonation, and light body.

It pours an opaque ruby with a small pinkish head. The aroma is somewhere between maraschino cherries and natural cherries, and the taste is reminiscent of the center of a cherry cordial. Theres a low level of carbonation, and its a bit slick.
beer_name: Samuel Smiths Organic Cherry Fruit Beer

review_blob: The beer pours a clear straw color with a small white head. The aroma is light with grains and dough yeast coming through, and the taste is slightly sweet and a touch sour with a super light, grainy aftertaste. The palate fuses a slick texture, medium body, and a soft carbonation.

The beer pours a very clear yellow with a medium white head. The aroma blends pils malt and doughy yeast, and the taste is slightly bitter and slightly sweet on the front end with more sour lager flavor coming through in the end. The palate fuses a slick texture, medium-light body, and a soft carbonation.

The beer pours a cloudy burnt orange, which is made murky by all the sediment floating throughout, and it has a small off-white head that fades quickly. The aroma blends pine, citrus juice, and pineapple, and the taste is mildly bitter and slightly sour. The initial flavor is bitter and dank pine hops; some citrus flavors come in and help cut through the dense hop flavor, but its not enough to save this beer from being too bitter for its flavors. The palate also doesnt lift the flavor from the tongue due to the thick texture, medium body, and soft carbonation.

The aroma on the beer blends lactic acid, wheat, and passion fruit. It pours a cloudy straw color with a small white head. The taste is quite sour on the front end, but a mild sweetness emerges in the middle and helps cut through the sourness. The aftertaste is only slightly sour, and it doesnt overwhelm the tongue. The palate has an average carbonation and light body.

It pours a very clear, very very light yellow color with no head. The aroma blends pears and yeast, and the taste is slightly sweet and slightly sour. Its rather dry and crisp, but there really isnt much to it. The palate, as expected, has a thin texture, light body, and a soft carbonation.

The beer is golden with a medium white head, and it has so much sediment floating throughout. The beer has a pine and citrus aroma, and the taste is quite bitter and slightly sweet with the hop bitterness hitting the tongue first and only fading slightly through the aftertaste. The palate fuses a slick and thin texture, light body, and a soft carbonation.

The beer pours black with a medium khaki-colored head, and the aroma blends resinous hops, roasted coffee beans, and pine needles. The taste is mildly bitter which comes from both the malt roast as well as the hops; there is also a slight amount of umami that helps balances the roasted malt flavors with the bitter American hops. The palate fuses a soft carbonation, medium-light body, and an oily texture, which does a good job of hiding this beers high ABV.

The beer pours a clear yellow color with a medium white head that fades quickly. The aroma has string lager yeast and grainy notes, much like that of a macro lager, just without a strong corn facet. It takes like a typical American adjunct lager, just with a touch more fruity hops, but its still slightly sour and slightly sweet. The palate fuses a slick texture, medium body, and a soft carbonation.

The beer pours very black with a small khaki-colored head. The aroma blends citrus and resin hops, astringent booze, and low levels of roast, and the taste is quite bitter with strong resinous and grassy hops dominating the tongue. The citrus flavors do bring a slight sweetness to the taste, but its not enough to cut through the roast bitterness that arises in the middle of the flavor on top of the hops; the aftertaste fades to hop flavor without too much roast remaining. The palate fuses a thick texture, medium body, and a soft carbonation.
beer_name: Bells Planet Series: Uranus - The Magician

review_blob: Th beer pours a slightly hazy orangeish golden color with a small white head. The aroma has a strong dough yeast smell, but there is also a pale malt sweetness and a hint of fruitiness. The taste is mildly sweet and slightly sour, and the sweetness hits the tongue first with more sour, slinky, and even slightly fruity flavors developing later in the taste. The palate fuses a a slick texture, medium body, and a soft carbonation. Overall, its not bad, but its not too good either.

The beer pours a hazy orange with a medium white head. The aroma blends pit fruit, caramel, and treacle. The taste is mildly sweet and slightly umami with not as many dark malt sweetness as I would expect from this style. The palate fuses a soft carbonation, medium body, and a slick texture.

The beer pours a clear orange with a large white head that fades slowly. The aroma blends earthy, floral, and resin hops, and the taste is slightly bitter and a touch sour with the earthy, herbal hops (despite how some cereal malt is in the background) dominating the taste. The aftertaste is a light version of the flavor, and the palate has a soft carbonation, slick texture, and a medium-light body.

The beer pours a hazy orange with a large rocky off-white head. The aroma blends resin and citrus hops with a hint of pils malt. The taste is mildly bitter and slightly sweet with resinous and piney flavors intensifying in the aftertaste. The palate fuses a sticky texture, medium body, and a soft carbonation.

The beer pours a deep, dark brown color with a small khaki-colored head that disappears quickly. The aroma contains caramel malts, wood, vanilla, toffee notes; the taste is quite umami, slightly sweet, slightly boozy, and a touch bitter, and the flavors were reminiscent of wood, tobacco, vanilla, and bourbon. Despite the high ABV, this beer was smooth, and its full body, oily and thick texture, and flat carbonation matched the flavors perfectly.

The beer pours black with a large tan head. The aroma blends cinnamon, cocoa powder, and a hint of chilis, and the taste is mildly bitter, slightly sweet, and a touch of spice (cinnamon) with chocolate and cinnamon flavors dominating. The palate fuses a medium body, slick texture, and a soft carbonation.
beer_name: Boulevard Smokestack Series - Imperial Stout X - Aztec Chocolate

review_blob: The beer pours a cloudy brownish red with a medium light tan head. The aroma blends toasted and chocolate malts, toffee, walnuts, and caramel, and the taste is mildly sweet and mildly umami with dark fruit flavors blending nicely with malty sweetness. The palate fuses a thick texture, soft carbonation, and a medium body.
UPDATED: MAR 16, 2016

The beer pours a cloudy yellow color with a large white head that fades somewhat slowly. The aroma blends a lot of Brett funk with citrusy hops, and the taste is mildly sweet, slightly funky, and a touch bitter. The palate fuses a slick texture, light body, and an average carbonation. Overall, this beer highlights Brett very well with funk being at the forefront with only the necessary hops to help it from getting too funky.

The beer pours a brownish red with a small off-white head that fades quickly. The aroma blends roasted and caramel malts, and the taste is slightly umami and slightly sweet with strong nutty and subtle cocoa flavors. The palate does have a thin texture and medium-light body, but the carbonation does match nicely with the flavors dancing on the tongue.

The brew pours like a dark soda does: brown color with a small white head that fades quickly. The aroma has a strong sweetness to it due to heavy vanilla, and the taste is very sweet and not much else. The flavor is similar to non-alcoholic root beer but is a bit more yeasty and vanilla. The palate fuses slick texture, medium-light body, and a lively carbonation.
beer_name: Root Sellers Row Hard Root Beer

beer_brewer_name: The Traveler Beer Company (formerly House Of Shandy)
review_blob: The beer pours a opaque golden color with a large white head that fades quickly. The aroma has a lot of lemon juice and zest, and the taste is slightly bitter and mildly sweet with a lot of lemon flavor without much else to it. The palate fuses an average carbonation, medium body, and a thick texture.

This mead pours a very clear golden color with no head. The aroma blends campfire, fresh jalapenos, and honey; the taste is surprisingly well balanced between a mild sweetness, mild smokiness, and a touch of spice, but there is definitely more jalapeno flavor than heat with the pineapple and honey flavors coming in to help balance the more extreme aspects of the flavor. In fact, its reminiscent grilled pineapple and jalapeno kabobs with the fresh flavors in the forefront and the char in the aftertaste. The palate fuses a slick texture, medium-light body, and a flat carbonation. I could see how this isnt for everyone, but I really enjoy it.

The beer pours a clear red color with a large off white head. The aroma blends nice caramel malts with resin, piney, and citrus hops, and the taste is mildly bitter and slightly sweet. The palate fuses a slick texture, medium-light body, and a soft carbonation.

The beer pours a pinkish orange with a large pinkish white head that settles quickly. The aroma blends hibiscus, chamomile, lemon juice, and hay, and the taste is mildly sour and a touch sweet with a definitive floral flavor throughout with the sourness mellowing through the aftertaste. The palate fuses a lively carbonation, light body, and thin texture.

The beer pours a mostly clear mahogany with a small off-white head, but there is some small-grain sediment floating throughout. The aroma blends bourbon, oak, toffee, caramel, and almond; the taste is mildly sweet, slightly umami, and a touch bitter with malty sweet flavors (amaretto, caramel, toffee) running throughout with a slight bourbon kick coming through more in the aftertaste. The palate fuses a slick texture, medium body, and a soft carbonation.
beer_name: Bells Planet Series: Saturn - The Bringer Of Old Age

review_blob: The beer pours a slightly hazy golden with a pinkish/purplish hue with a small white head. The aroma blends salt and blackberries, and the taste is slightly sour, slightly sweet, and a touch salt. The initial flavor is blackberry tartness, but the aftertaste reveals a little more salt and balanced sourness and astringency (even if the overall sourness is still fairly light). The palate fuses a medium-light body, slick and thick texture, and a soft carbonation.

The beer pours a hazy yellow color with a medium white head, and the aroma blends mango, acidity, oak, and white pepper. The taste is mildly sour and a touch sweet with strong mango flavors and acidity running throughout. The palate fuses a slick texture, light body, and a soft carbonation.
beer_name: Jolly Pumpkin Forgotten Tales of the Last Gypsy Series 1 Vol. 1

review_blob: The beer pours a clear golden with a medium white head. The aroma is full of hops: lemon, orange, pine, resin, and grapefruit. The taste is mildly bitter and mildly sweet with loads of citrus and pine flavor and a bitter, earthy, piney, grassy finish. The palate fuses a slick texture, medium-light body, and an average carbonation. Overall, this beer is delicious, hides its booze well, and brings a huge citrus flavor to the table; there isnt too much more that Id like to see out of a DIPA like this one.
beer_name: Boulevard Smokestack Series - The Calling IPA

review_blob: The beer pours a very clear light orange color with a medium white head that fades quickly. The aroma blends light malts and resin hops, and the taste is mildly bitter and a touch sour with an aftertaste that is grassy in addition to resiny. The palate fuses a medium-light body, lively carbonation, and a slightly sticky texture. Overall, the beer is one-dimensional, and that one dimension isnt that great.

The beer pours a very clear orange color with a medium white head. The aroma blends citrus and resin hops, but the hops are so heavy that they overpower any malt there is. The taste, though, is a lot more balanced with a mild sweetness (from both the malts and citrus hops) and a slight bitterness with a piney hop flavor emerging in the aftertaste. The palate fuses a slick texture, medium-light body, and a soft carbonation.

The beer pours a hazy golden with a small white head. The aroma blends lager yeast, pils malt, and a touch a spicy hops. The taste is mildly sweet and slightly bitter with lots of grainy flavor and some citrus hop character. The palate fuses a thick texture, soft carbonation, and a medium body.

The beer pours like a hefeweizen should with streaks of yeast and opaque dark golden color, but the medium white head did fade quickly. The aroma had a lot of banana, but there was some underlying wheat sweetness and hint of clove; the taste was similar with a mild sweetness and a touch of sourness coming directly from a heavy banana flavor throughout the drinking experience. The palate had a nice medium body and thick texture, but the carbonation was a bit too soft for the other elements of the beer, resulting in a heavy drink by the end of the glass.
UPDATED: JUN 30, 2015
beer_name: Big Muddy Saluki Dunkeldog Dark Amber

review_blob: The beer pours a hazy golden color with a medium white head that fades quickly, and the aroma blends Belgian yeast, sour fruit, and grains. The taste is mildly bitter, slightly sour, and a touch sweet with a lot of Belgian yeast and not much cherry to back it up, and the aftertaste is a bit sulfury. The palate fuses an average carbonation, thin texture, and a medium-light body.

The beer pours a very clear amber color with a medium white head. The aroma blends pils malt and grassy hops, and the taste is slightly sweet and a touch bitter with an overall flavor thats very light and unoffensive. The palate fuses an average carbonation, light body, and a thin texture.

The beer pours a cloudy golden color with a large white head that fades somewhat quickly. The aroma has a lot of banana, but there is also some wheat sweetness and vanilla. The taste is quite sweet and a touch sour with a strong banana flavor supported by wheat graininess. The palate has an average carbonation, which should feel pleasant on the tongue, but the thin texture and medium-light body dont support that carbonation bite on the tongue.

The beer pours a very clear dark orange color with a small white head, and the aroma blends resin and piney hops (which dominate), oak, sour fruit, and a hint of Belgian yeast. The taste is mildly bitter, slightly sweet, and a touch sour with an aftertaste reminiscent of the hop aromas. If I wasnt told it was a blend, I would hardly be able to pick up the Belgian nuances in the beer. The palate fuses an average carbonation, medium-light body, and a slick texture.
beer_name: Stone / Ecliptic / Wicked Weed Points Unknown IPA

beer_brewer_name: The Traveler Beer Company (formerly House Of Shandy)
review_blob: This beer looks ugly in the glass; its opaque and murky with a small white head, and the color is dark golden with a pinkish hue. The aroma is mostly just grapefruit juice, but there is an underlying straw and lemon scent. The taste is slightly sour and a touch sweet with an aftertaste that is distinctly Fruit Loops rather than too much grapefruit. The palate fuses a thick texture, nearly flat carbonation, and a medium body.

The beer pours a very clear dark straw color with a small white head that fades quickly. The aroma blends lager yeast, pils malt, and a touch of resin hops. The major flavor is graininess, and the taste is a touch sweet and slightly umami with the typical sour lager bite. The palate fuses an average carbonation, medium-light body, and a thin and slick texture.

The cider pours an opaque golden orange, and the aroma smells like orange juice and apple juice. The taste is quite sweet and a touch sour, but the flavor is like a fusion of apple and orange juice. The palate has a medium-light body, slick texture, and a soft carbonation.
UPDATED: JUN 27, 2015

The beer pours a slightly golden with a large white head. The aroma blends lemons, tropical fruits (pineapple), citrus hops, and some light malts. The taste is mildly bitter and mildy sweet with a piney aftertaste. The palate fuses a slightly sticky texture, medium-light body, and a soft carbonation.

The beer pours a hazy orange color with an enormous off-white head that fades slowly. The aroma blends acidity, sour fruit, and some low-level caramel malts. The taste is mildly sour and a touch sweet with a slightly oak flavor alongside some sour fruit notes. The palate fuses a medium body, slick texture, and a soft carbonation.

The beer pours a very clear straw color with a small white head that fades quickly. The aroma is quite skunky, but there is some clean Pils malt hovering underneath the skunk. The taste is slightly sweet and a touch bitter with a nearly non-existent aftertaste. The palate fuses a medium-light body, soft carbonation, and a thin and slick texture.

The beer pours an opaque gold color with a small white head that fades quickly. The aroma blends orange juice, lemon zest, coriander, and wheat sweetness, and the taste is slightly sweet and a bit one-dimensional. The aftertaste doesnt have the typical American wheat yeast flavor, which is a plus, and the aftertaste just has some light fruit and wheat flavor. The palate fuses a thick texture, medium body, and a soft carbonation.
